Getting started
Prerequisites
You need Java 21 and Maven. On macOS with Homebrew:
brew install openjdk@21 maven
Run the app
# Set up Java 21 if it's not your default
export JAVA_HOME="$(brew --prefix openjdk@21)/libexec/openjdk.jdk/Contents/Home"
export PATH="$JAVA_HOME/bin:$PATH"

# Launch
mvn javafx:run
Run the tests
export JAVA_HOME="$(brew --prefix openjdk@21)/libexec/openjdk.jdk/Contents/Home"
export PATH="$JAVA_HOME/bin:$PATH"

mvn test
Where your data lives
CipherVault keeps everything under your home directory:
~/.ciphervault/
├── ciphervault.db     ← SQLite database (metadata + audit log)
└── vault/             ← Encrypted file blobs
Nothing is written anywhere else and nothing leaves your machine.
How the security works
On setup
 — your master password is hashed with 
 (random salt, 310 000 iterations) and stored. The same password is used to derive the AES key.
On login
 — the entered password is re-derived and compared against the stored hash. Wrong password means no access.
On import
 — the file is read into memory, encrypted with AES-256-GCM (random IV), and written to 
. Only the ciphertext ever touches disk.
On export
 — the encrypted blob is decrypted in memory and written to your chosen destination.
`PBKDF2WithHmacSHA256``~/.ciphervault/vault/`
